{"title_page": "John II of Cyprus", "text_new": "{{unreferenced|date=January 2009}}\n{{ infobox royalty\n| name        = John II\n| image       = John Poitiers-Lusignan 1418-58.jpeg\n| succession  = King of Cyprus\n| reign       = 29 June 1432 \u2013 28 July 1458\n| predecessor = [[Janus of Cyprus|Janus]]\n| successor   = [[Charlotte, Queen of Cyprus|Charlotte]]\n| house       = [[Poitiers-Lusignan]]\n| father      = [[Janus of Cyprus]]\n| mother      = [[Charlotte of Bourbon, Queen of Cyprus|Charlotte of Bourbon]]\n| spouse      = [[Amadea Palaiologina of Montferrat]]<br/>[[Helena Palaiologina]]\n| issue       = [[Charlotte of Cyprus]]<br>[[James II of Cyprus]]\n| birth_date  = 16 May 1418\n| birth_place = \n| death_date  = 28 July 1458\n| death_place = \n}}\n'''John II''' or '''III of Cyprus''' (16 May 1418 &ndash; 28 July 1458) was the [[King of Cyprus]] and [[Armenian Cilicia|Armenia]] and also titular [[King of Jerusalem]] from 1432 to 1458. He was previously a titular [[Prince of Antioch]].\n\nJohn was the son of king [[Janus of Cyprus]] and [[Charlotte of Bourbon, Queen of Cyprus|Charlotte of Bourbon]]; he was born and died in [[Nicosia]].  In May, sometime between 1435 and 1440, he married Aimee or [[Amadea Palaiologina of Monferrato]] (3 August 1429 &ndash; [[Nicosia]], 13 September 1440), daughter of [[John Jacob of Montferrat|John Jacob Palaiologos]], [[Marquess of Montferrat]], without issue. His second wife, a distant relative of his first one, whom he married in Nicosia in 1441 or on 3 February 1442, was [[Helena Palaiologina]] (1428 &ndash; 11 April 1458), only child and daughter of [[Theodore II Palaiologos]], [[Despot of the Morea]] and his wife [[Cleofa Malatesta]]. Theodore was a son of [[Byzantine Emperor]] [[Manuel II Palaiologos]] and [[Helena Draga\u0161]] and the brother of the last two Byzantine emperors, [[John VIII Palaiologos]] and [[Constantine XI Palaiologos]]. By his second marriage he had two daughters:\n* [[Charlotte of Cyprus|Charlotte of Lusignan]]\n* Cleopha of Lusignan, died young\n\nUpon the death of John II, his only surviving legitimate child Charlotte succeeded to the throne. During his rule, [[Corycus]], the only Cypriot stronghold in mainland [[Anatolia]] was lost to the [[Karamanids]] in 1448.\n\nJohn had an illegitimate son by [[Marietta de Patras]]\n* [[James II of Cyprus|James]]\nwhom he appointed [[Archbishop of Nicosia]] at the age of 16. James did not prove ideal archbishop material, and was stripped of his title after murdering the royal [[Chamberlain (office)|chamberlain]]. His father eventually forgave him and restored him to the Archbishopric. James and Helena were enemies, vying for influence over John. After Helena died in 1458, it appeared that John would appoint James as his successor, but John died before he could make it so.\n\nHe was the last direct legitimate male descendant of [[Raymond of Antioch|Raymond de Poitiers]] of Antioch, a younger son of [[William IX of Aquitaine]].\n\n== Ancestry ==\n{{unsourced section|date=April 2019}}\n{{ahnentafel\n|collapsed=yes |align=center\n|boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc;\n|boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9;\n|boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc;\n|boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc;\n|boxstyle_5=background-color: #9fe;\n| 1=  1. '''John II of Cyprus'''\n| 2=  2. [[Janus of Cyprus]]\n| 3=  3. [[Charlotte of Bourbon, Queen of Cyprus]]\n| 4=  4. [[James I of Cyprus]]\n| 5=  5. [[Helvis of Brunswick-Grubenhagen]]\n| 6=  6. [[John I, Count of La Marche]]\n| 7=  7. [[Catherine of Vend\u00f4me]]\n| 8=  8. [[Hugh IV of Cyprus]]\n| 9=  9. [[Alix of Ibelin]]\n|10= 10. [[Philip of Brunswick-Grubenhagen]]\n|11= 11. Helvis de Dampierre\n|12= 12. [[James I, Count of La Marche]]\n|13= 13. [[Jeanne of Ch\u00e2tillon]]\n|14= 14. [[John VI of Vend\u00f4me]]\n|15= 15. [[Joan of Ponthieu, Dame of Epernon]]\n|16= 16. [[Guy constable of Cyprus|Guy of Poitiers-Lusignan]]\n|17= 17. [[Eschive d'Ibelin (1253\u20131312)|Eschive d'Ibelin]]\n|18= 18. [[Guy of Ibelin (1286\u20131308)|Guy of Ibelin]]\n|19= 19. [[Isabella of Ibelin (died 1315)|Isabella of Ibelin]]\n|20= 20. [[Henry II, Duke of Brunswick-Grubenhagen]]\n|21= 21. Heloise d' Ibelin\n|22= 22. Eudes de Dampierre\n|23= 23. Isabelle de Lusignan\n|24= 24. [[Louis I, Duke of Bourbon]]\n|25= 25. [[Mary of Avesnes]]\n|26= 26. [[Gaucher V de Ch\u00e2tillon]]\n|27= 27. Isabelle de Dreux\n|28= 28. Bouchard VI\n|29= 29. Alix de Bretagne\n|30= 30. Jean II de Ponthieu\n|31= 31. Catherine d'Artois\n}}\n\n[[File:Armoiries Arm\u00e9nie-Lusignan.svg|thumb|left|150px|coat-of-arms of Lusignan of Cyprus, Jerusalem and Lesser Armenia]]\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-reg}}\n{{s-bef | rows=2| before = [[Janus of Cyprus|Janus]] }}\n{{s-ttl | title = [[King of Cyprus]]\n        | years = 1432&ndash;1458 }}\n{{s-aft | rows=2| after  = [[Charlotte of Cyprus|Charlotte]] }}\n|-\n{{s-tul | title = [[King of Jerusalem]]<br />[[King of Armenian Cilicia]]\n        | years = 1432&ndash;1458 }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Cypriot Monarchs}}\n{{Antioch Monarchs}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:John 02 Of Cyprus}}\n[[Category:Kings of Cyprus]]\n[[Category:Kings of the Armenian Kingdom of Cilicia]]\n[[Category:1418 births]]\n[[Category:1458 deaths]]\n[[Category:15th century in Cyprus]]\n[[Category:Claimant Kings of Jerusalem]]\n[[Category:House of Poitiers-Lusignan]]\n", "text_old": "{{unreferenced|date=January 2009}}\n{{ infobox royalty\n| name        = John II\n| image       = John Poitiers-Lusignan 1418-58.jpeg\n| succession  = King of Cyprus\n| reign       = 29 June 1432 \u2013 28 July 1458\n| predecessor = [[Janus of Cyprus|Janus]]\n| successor   = [[Charlotte, Queen of Cyprus|Charlotte]]\n| house       = [[Poitiers-Lusignan]]\n| father      = [[Janus of Cyprus]]\n| mother      = [[Charlotte of Bourbon, Queen of Cyprus|Charlotte of Bourbon]]\n| spouse      = [[Amadea Palaiologina of Montferrat]]<br/>[[Helena Palaiologina]]\n| issue       = [[Charlotte of Cyprus]]<br>[[James II of Cyprus]]\n| birth_date  = 16 May 1418\n| birth_place = \n| death_date  = 28 July 1458\n| death_place = \n}}\n'''John II''' or '''III of Cyprus''' (16 May 1418 &ndash; 28 July 1458) was the [[King of Cyprus]] and [[Armenian Cilicia|Armenia]] and also titular [[King of Jerusalem]] from 1432 to 1458. He was previously a titular [[Prince of Antioch]].\n\nJohn was the son of king [[Janus of Cyprus]] and [[Charlotte of Bourbon, Queen of Cyprus|Charlotte of Bourbon]]; he was born and died in [[Nicosia]].  In May, sometime between 1435 and 1440, he married Aimee or [[Amadea Palaiologina of Monferrato]] (3 August 1429 &ndash; [[Nicosia]], 13 September 1440), daughter of [[John Jacob of Montferrat|John Jacob Palaiologos]], [[Marquess of Montferrat]], without issue. His second wife, a distant relative of his first one, whom he married in Nicosia in 1441 or on 3 February 1442, was [[Helena Palaiologina]] (1428 &ndash; 11 April 1458), only child and daughter of [[Theodore II Palaiologos]], [[Despot of the Morea]] and his wife [[Cleofa Malatesta]]. Theodore was a son of [[Byzantine Emperor]] [[Manuel II Palaiologos]] and [[Helena Draga\u0161]] and the brother of the last two Byzantine emperors, [[John VIII Palaiologos]] and [[Constantine XI Palaiologos]]. By his second marriage he had two daughters:\n* [[Charlotte of Cyprus|Charlotte of Lusignan]]\n* Cleopha of Lusignan, died young\n\nUpon the death of John II, his only surviving legitimate child Charlotte succeeded to the throne. During his rule, [[Corycus]], the only Cypriot stronghold in mainland [[Anatolia]] was lost to the [[Karamanids]] in 1448.\n\nJohn had an illegitimate son by [[Marietta de Patras]]\n* [[James II of Cyprus|James]]\nwhom he appointed [[Archbishop of Nicosia]] at the age of 16. James did not prove ideal archbishop material, and was stripped of his title after murdering the royal [[Chamberlain (office)|chamberlain]]. His father eventually forgave him and restored him to the Archbishopric. James and Helena were enemies, vying for influence over John. After Helena died in 1458, it appeared that John would appoint James as his successor, but John died before he could make it so.\n\nHe was the last direct legitimate male descendant of [[Raymond of Antioch|Raymond de Poitiers]] of Antioch, a younger son of [[William IX of Aquitaine]].\n\n== Ancestry ==\n{{unsourced section|date=April 2019}}\n{{ahnentafel\n|collapsed=yes |align=center\n|boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc;\n|boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9;\n|boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc;\n|boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc;\n|boxstyle_5=background-color: #9fe;\n| 1 = '''John II of Cyprus'''\n| 2 = [[Janus of Cyprus]]\n| 3 = [[Charlotte of Bourbon, Queen of Cyprus]]\n| 4 = [[James I of Cyprus]]\n| 5 = [[Helvis of Brunswick-Grubenhagen]]\n| 6 = [[John I, Count of La Marche]]\n| 7 = [[Catherine of Vend\u00f4me]]\n| 8 = [[Hugh IV of Cyprus]]\n| 9 = [[Alix of Ibelin]]\n| 10= [[Philip of Brunswick-Grubenhagen]]\n| 11= Helvis de Dampierre\n| 12= [[James I, Count of La Marche]]\n| 13= Jeanne of Ch\u00e2tillon\n| 14= [[John VI of Vend\u00f4me]]\n| 15= Joan of Ponthieu, Dame of Epernon\n}}\n\n[[File:Armoiries Arm\u00e9nie-Lusignan.svg|thumb|left|150px|coat-of-arms of Lusignan of Cyprus, Jerusalem and Lesser Armenia]]\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-reg}}\n{{s-bef | rows=2| before = [[Janus of Cyprus|Janus]] }}\n{{s-ttl | title = [[King of Cyprus]]\n        | years = 1432&ndash;1458 }}\n{{s-aft | rows=2| after  = [[Charlotte of Cyprus|Charlotte]] }}\n|-\n{{s-tul | title = [[King of Jerusalem]]<br />[[King of Armenian Cilicia]]\n        | years = 1432&ndash;1458 }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Cypriot Monarchs}}\n{{Antioch Monarchs}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:John 02 Of Cyprus}}\n[[Category:Kings of Cyprus]]\n[[Category:Kings of the Armenian Kingdom of Cilicia]]\n[[Category:1418 births]]\n[[Category:1458 deaths]]\n[[Category:15th century in Cyprus]]\n[[Category:Claimant Kings of Jerusalem]]\n[[Category:House of Poitiers-Lusignan]]\n", "name_user": "ArisMethymna", 